Because `exchangeToken(...)` is private and uses chained `WebClient`, the cleanest option is to extract token exchange into its own service.

## Recommended small refactor

Create:

```text
service/OidcTokenService.java
```

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OidcTokenService {

    private final WebClient webClient;

    public Map<String, Object> exchangeToken(
            String code,
            String tokenUrl,
            AppConfigResponse appConfig,
            AuthTransaction tx
    ) {
        return webClient.post()
                .uri(tokenUrl)
                .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_FORM_URLENCODED)
                .body(BodyInserters.fromFormData("grant_type", "authorization_code")
                        .with("client_id", appConfig.getClientId())
                        .with("client_secret", appConfig.getClientSecret())
                        .with("code", code)
                        .with("redirect_uri", tx.getRedirectUri())
                        .with("code_verifier", tx.getCodeVerifier()))
                .retrieve()
                .onStatus(HttpStatusCode::isError, clientResponse ->
                        clientResponse.bodyToMono(String.class)
                                .flatMap(body -> Mono.error(
                                        new TechnicalException("Token exchange failed: " + body))))
                .bodyToMono(new ParameterizedTypeReference<Map<String, Object>>() {})
                .block();
    }
}
```

Then inject it into `AuthService`:

```java
private final OidcTokenService oidcTokenService;
```

Replace:

```java
Map<String, Object> tokenResponse = exchangeToken(code, tokenUrl, appConfig, tx);
```

with:

```java
Map<String, Object> tokenResponse =
        oidcTokenService.exchangeToken(code, tokenUrl, appConfig, tx);
```

Now tests become easy.

