But since you don’t want `eq(...)`, don’t match complex objects. Use:

```java
when(oidcTokenService.exchangeToken(
        anyString(),
        anyString(),
        any(AppConfigResponse.class),
        any(AuthTransaction.class)
)).thenReturn(null);
```

Full test:

```java
@Test
void handleCallback_shouldThrowTechnicalException_whenTokenResponseIsNull() {
    when(redisAuthTransactionService.findByState("state-123"))
            .thenReturn(authTransaction());
    when(partnerRepositoryClient.getApp("B2BOOST_BE"))
            .thenReturn(validAppConfig());
    when(oidcDiscoveryClient.loadMetadata("issuer-uri"))
            .thenReturn(metadata());
    when(oidcTokenService.exchangeToken(
            anyString(),
            anyString(),
            any(AppConfigResponse.class),
            any(AuthTransaction.class)
    )).thenReturn(null);

    assertThatThrownBy(() -> authService.handleCallback("auth-code", "state-123"))
            .isInstanceOf(TechnicalException.class)
            .hasMessage("Token response is null");
}
```

